„Yes, Captain. They should be on the move by now, they were still in the mess hall to pick up their rations.“         At exactly 0500, the Exodus Company gathered at the vehicle park. Shaw climbed onto a box and began speaking.
„We will be moved to the forward deployment base I-131, fifty miles outside of Ianlos. Our task is to support the ongoing siege and later the attack on Ianlos to drive out the rebels. There we will establish a base at the foot of the mountains,“ explained Shaw. „March to your squads and mount up.“
The company broke into its respective squads, and the soldiers were assigned to the tanks by the non-commissioned officers. Cohren climbed into one of the tanks further up in the convoy, where he met Nemic, Craith, and two new recruits. Cohren remembered the day when the two arrived a few days ago, but knew little about them. He sat sideways and let his legs dangle while he adjusted his backpack and the radio equipment, which was connected to his headset and throat microphone.
„Hey Cohren, is Snowball still with Harris?“, asked Nemic after they had settled in.
„Do you mean the rooster he stole?“ Cohren recalled the morning when they allowed the bird to leave with a farmer. „Yes, I think so.“
Cohren schaute zu einem der anderen Panzer hinüber und entdeckte Harris mit seinem Trupp. Aus dem Augenwinkel konnte er die Bewegung eines kleinen Hahns ausmachen, der durch ständiges Drehen des Kopfes die Umgebung absuchte.
„Ja, er ist noch bei ihm“, antwortete Cohren, als sich die Luke des Panzers öffnete und der Kommandant in Sicht kam.
„Alle Panzer rücken aus“, sprach der Kommandeur langsam und ruhig in sein Headset. Die Motoren des Zuges aus Panzern und Strykern heulten auf, als sie sich in Bewegung setzten. Der Kronos-Panzer, auf dem Cohren mitfuhr, rüttelte, als die Bremse gelöst wurde und sie sich in die Formation einreihten. Die Panzer bewegten sich in keilförmiger Formation über die Itania-Ebene. Durch die winterlichen Stürme waren die Sumpfgebiete zugefroren und die Wälder verschneit, trotzdem war der Schlamm allgegenwärtig.
Nach etwa einer Stunde begann einer der Rekruten, von dem Cohren wusste, dass er Orson hieß, zu sprechen. „Leutnant, Sie sind seit Kriegsbeginn hier, richtig?“
„Ja, Operation Feuersturm“, antwortete Cohren. „Wir dachten, die Sache wäre in ein paar Wochen erledigt, aber wir haben sie unterschätzt.“
“Underestimating them is strongly underestimated,” Nemic interjected into the conversation. “We were not prepared for their arsenal and the number of soldiers. They destroyed the UFS Revenant in the first two weeks and only took down the Erebus last month. We should even see them on our way.”
“I stand firmly by the side of the Federation,” Orson said defiantly. “I will not let these terrorists scare me.”
“You say that now. But I have seen that most eighteen-year-old recruits like you take cover very quickly as soon as they hear a shot,” Craith explained.
“We’ll see about that,” Cohren said laughing. Orson ended the conversation.
“Exodus XO, Exodus CO,” Cohren’s radio crackled. “We receive warm signatures, approximately 300 meters away, 20 degrees right.”
Cohren climbed up on the tank and put on his special glasses. When he switched them to "Infrared," he could recognize the signatures in the distance.
“Yes, I see them,” Cohren replied through his throat microphone.
“Are they hostile?” asked the other recruit, Natayla.
“I can't determine that,” answered Cohren. He reached for his microphone and said: “Exodus Company, first engage when under fire. We'll lure them out.”
As they approached, the point-like heat signatures took shape. As they came even closer, one of them hurried off to get something. Immediately, she returned to the small hillock where the others were positioned. The figures lay down on the ground and assumed firing positions.
“We have enemy contact,” Shaw called over the radio as orange tracer bullets were fired from the hilltop. While the tanks were under fire, the assault troops jumped down and took cover. A rocket flew past and exploded into the ground behind the formation, scattering debris and rock onto one of the tanks. Another struck a Stryker, an APS-Cerberus, and exploded. The crew quickly got out and took cover as the ammunition went up in flames.
“Iron 1-2 and 1-3, 25 degrees right, 300 meters. Fire,” the commander of the tank column shouted over the radio. Iron 1-2 and 1-3 opened fire, grenades flying toward the hilltop and exploding, throwing dirt and stone into the air.
“Send the Sentis in,” Knoxx called, observing the hilltop through binoculars. The rear hatch of a Cerberus opened, and an unarmed soldier wearing a special headset came out. He shouted commands into a square microphone, and two Sentis, officially called Sentinels, charged out. With their thin, metallic arms and legs swinging forward, they sprinted. They carried their weapons on their backs.
“Kill or capture?” Craith asked, watching.
“Looks like capture,” Cohren speculated, as the two Sentinels disappeared into the cloud of ash and smoke. Screams and gunfire echoed from the hilltop but soon died down. Shortly after, the two Sentinels returned, dragging someone behind them whose boots left tracks in the ground. Once they had returned to the protection of the column, they threw the figure onto the ground. She groaned in pain as she landed hard in the mud and snow.
Shaw went to the figure that was just trying to stand up. Then he turned to one of the Sentinels. "How many?"
""Three dead, sir," answered the Sentinel. 'The rest fled on foot,'
Shaw nodded and turned to Cohren and Craith, who were nearby. "Get this guy out of my sight!"
